Casablanca,t2jBSAWCg5s,UgzaeO5N_oLNeG4C-Et4AaABAg,,@richardcanedo1614,"There is a ""reading"" of this film on a geo-political level. Rick is the USA who once loved and got involved in Europe (in World War I and after), so Ilsa is Europe. But circumstances there separated them, so the US retreated into isolation and cynicism about noble causes like democracy -- or love -- nand that's where we find Rick/US at the start of the film. But now Europe/Ilsa is back and is in desperate need. The Bulgarian refugee woman reminds Rick of the power and self-sacrifice love can call for: he helps her out of her need to sacrifice, but later, when he's gotten past his bitterness over being left by Ilsa/Europe, he decides to do the right thing: save Ilsa and all the good she carries with her (Victor), and go on to fight for her/Europe and for high ideals, even if it means he'll never see or love her again. But they'll always have Paris.",2026-05-12T00:40:05Z,2026-05-12T00:40:05Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-14T02:01:06.868028
