Casablanca,t2jBSAWCg5s,UgwOxOsP57S6MvPkgJZ4AaABAg,,@lemorab1,"A video used to be on YouTube (maybe it was about the making of ""Casablanca"") that commented on the scene in Rick's Cafe where the camera pans over various refugees trying to pawn their jewelry, etc. to buy their way out of ""Casablanca;"" trying to buy exit visas, pay smugglers, and hire boats. The video gave the names and backgrounds of these bit players, many of whom had held important jobs in the European film and theater industries, before fleeing for their lives. They lived very hard lives in the United States, never regaining the status and security they had enjoyed before Hitler came to power. Two of the noteworthy players in small supporting roles were Madeleine Le Beau, Rick's sometime girlfriend, and her husband Marcel Dalio, the croupier. They had a harrowing time leaving Europe. Yvonne's passionate singing of La Marseillaise and her flowing tears were not acting, they were real. At the time of filming, S. Z. Sakall (Carl the headwaiter) had three sisters and many other family members in Nazi concentration camps, and he had no idea if they were alive or dead. 

The Epstein brothers created the character of Ilsa Lund, partly based on Spanish painter Remedios Varo, in Marseilles when they were there, torn between two men, and trying to get out of Europe. (I read this in Janet Kaplan's biography of Varo, ""Unexpected Journeys."")

The movie never flags, moving along at a good clip, thanks to Director Michael Curtiz.",2026-05-03T04:33:41Z,2026-05-03T04:55:56Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-14T02:01:06.868426
