Casablanca,t2jBSAWCg5s,Ugz6uq2HQU6T5GgG0q94AaABAg,,@johnnehrich9601,"One of the things to keep in mind is that the VERY restrictive Hays Code was still in effect that censored movies in all sorts of ways.  It was adopted in the early 1930's and was replaced by our current multi-level letter code rating system in 1969  (and an entire decade's worth of zany movies that broke all the rules followed - Blazing Saddles, Airport, Naked Gun, Holy Grail, Life of Brian, Rocky Horror).

In the case of this movie, as long as the husband was still alive, the Code required that she stay with him - adultery of any form was prohibited.  (It is worth looking into the effect of the Code which explains a lot about the movies made during it and those made in the immediate freedom right afterwards.)

Among other things, even the most iconic line, the last one, from the blockbuster 1939 Gone With The Wind, ""Frankly my dear, I don't give a damn"" required lots of pressure.  The Code required words like ""pregnant,"" and ""whore"" (and all the variations on this), were NOT allowed. In the classic 1939 Stagecoach, modern audiences can't figure out why one woman is being driven out town (for moral reason) and the other is in the final stage of pregnancy, but the audiences knew exactly what the subtle clues indicated.

Even a married couple could NOT be seen sleeping in a double bed.  Any character who committed a criminal act HAD to be seen getting his just desserts by the end of the film.  Movies could not show any gore - guys got shot and all the audience saw there bloodless round holes.  (And Hitchcock's 1962Psycho really broke a lot of rules - they had to devise a way to show flowing blood because up that point, movies didn't show this.)",2026-05-02T22:04:45Z,2026-05-02T22:08:12Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-14T02:01:06.868502
